snippet.textDisplay:
9:15, to put that into perspective, think about this, the bit rate for 8k redcoderaw at 8:1 compression is ~164MB/sec. So, if the mac pro was processing it in real time, it would be processing 164 MEGABYTES in a second, but it isn't - its processing at faster than real-time, faster than 164MB/sec.

Also, since this is raw footage, and not prores, the $2000 afterburner card, specifically designed to help process video hasn't even kicked in yet, and since both FCPX and Da Vinci Resolve use gpus efficiency, and this isn't the top spec in terms of gpu, the mac pro can actually get much more powerful than this...

snippet.textDisplay:
I always have to wonder about creatives that are wowed by something with ACTUAL power after being used to macbook's and iMacs for so long. Like, for real Marques, you got money for cameras that are like 50 grand. Do you know what kind of PC you can get for that? What you COULD have been using for years and years that would have sped up your render times over your iMac for years??

Seriously. Workstations. Dell and HP makes professional-class workstations. The HP Z8 G4 workstation blows nearly everything else out of the water, if you have the budget for it. I configured one today and let me tell you, with like two Xeon 28-core processors, 1.5TB of RAM, all the SSD storage space you can imagine (in M.2 and PCIe forms too), toss in two of the highest end professional graphics cards I can, and pretty much max out everything on the system... I had a system that went for like $108,000
Earlier I saw somebody max out a Mac Pro at $53,000

So if money is no object and all you want is power... PC workstations. They could have been your go-to systems for years man. Imagine all the render time saved. Sure, no Final Cut, but thats a small price to pay.
